---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '@components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import { url } from '@lib/url';
import { SITE_NAME } from '@data/site';
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="What HeavyHiker is, who it's for, and the editorial rules that keep a gear site honest: verified weights, sourced claims, and no pretend field testing.">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-8">
    <Breadcrumbs crumbs={[{ label: 'Home', href: '/' }, { label: 'About' }]} />
    <h1 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">About {SITE_NAME}</h1>

    <div class="prose mt-6">
      <p>
        {SITE_NAME} exists because most backpacking gear content online is either a lifestyle magazine
        or an affiliate spreadsheet wearing a hiking hat. Both have the same problem: the numbers can't
        be trusted. Claimed weights get copied from press releases, "reviews" get written from product
        photos, and every third product is somehow essential.
      </p>
      <p>
        We keep a ledger instead. Every product gets its weight verified against the manufacturer's own
        spec sheet and recorded in ounces and grams. Every claim about durability or performance traces
        to verified owner reports or published third-party testing. Every unknown is printed as
        "not published" instead of a guess. The full method is on
        <a href={url('/how-we-review/')}>How We Review</a> — including what we deliberately don't do.
      </p>

      <h2>Who this is for</h2>
      <p>
        Thru-hikers and multi-day backpackers, beginner to intermediate. If you're planning a first
        weekend loop or your first long section hike and trying to spend money once, correctly — you're
        the reader. Everything is evaluated for gear you carry on your back, on foot, into the
        backcountry. We don't cover car camping, overlanding, or RV gear, ever.
      </p>

      <h2>How the site operates</h2>
      <p>
        {SITE_NAME} runs on a structured editorial pipeline that uses automation heavily: research
        aggregation, spec verification, and publishing checks are systematized, and every integrity rule
        is enforced by code that runs before anything goes live. Humans own the site, the methodology,
        and the responsibility for what it says. If we get a number wrong,
        <a href={url('/contact/')}>tell us</a> and we'll fix it and log the correction.
      </p>

      <h2>How the site makes money</h2>
      <p>
        Affiliate commissions, disclosed on every page that contains them and explained in full on the
        <a href={url('/affiliate-disclosure/')}>affiliate disclosure page</a>. No sponsored posts, no
        paid placements, no free gear in exchange for coverage.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
